   😦 synchronization 

     => Process synchronization is needed when multiple processes/threads share data or resources.

       👉 Only one process should enter the critical section at a time.

       ⚠️ Race Condition
           Occurs when multiple processes access shared data simultaneously
           Result depends on execution order
           
           👉 Leads to incorrect output

       🧠 Producer–Consumer Problem
             Two processes:
             Producer → produces data
             Consumer → consumes data
             They share a buffer
             ❗ Problem:
             Producer may overwrite data
             Consumer may read empty buffer
             
             👉 Needs synchronization (using semaphore/mutex) 
     
      
      🧠 Critical Section Problem in OS

          A critical section is a part of a program where shared data/resources are accessed.
          
          👉 The problem is to ensure that only one process executes in the critical section at a time.
          

         ⚠️ Why it is needed:
             To avoid race condition
             To maintain data consistency


        Entry Section   → request to enter  
        Critical Section → access shared resource  
        Exit Section    → release resource  
        Remainder Section → other work        

         ✅ Requirements (Conditions):
            1. Mutual Exclusion
            Only one process in critical section
            2. Progress
            If no process is inside, others should not wait unnecessarily
            3. Bounded Waiting
            Every process gets a chance (no starvation)    